^-{ ^*BDeal of the Week 288 - March 18, 2002^*N }
^-
I just finished playing 10 days of bridge at the ^*NACBL Spring North American Championships^*N in Houston and, as I am sure you can imagine, I got to see (and play) a lot of interesting deals. This week's deal was my personal favorite from Houston.

This week's deal took place in the 2nd last match of the North American Swiss Teams on Sunday. My team (partner ^*BBrad Moss^*N, ^*BRoy Welland^*N-^*BBjorn Fallenius^*N, and ^*BHoward Weinstein^*N-^*BSteve Garner^*N) was essentially tied for first at this point with the team of ^*BPerry Johnson^*N-^*BJeff Meckstroth^*N and ^*BEric Rodwell^*N-^*BPaul Soloway^*N going into this match. Our 2 teams had a pretty good lead over the rest of the field so there was a good chance that the winner of this match would go on to win the event.

|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


nt|I particularly wanted to win this match as our team lost early in the week to Meckstroth-Rodwell and Soloway (and with ^*BBob Hamman^*N, Soloway's partner, and ^*BNick Nickell^*N-^*BDick Freeman^*N. The stakes were higher in that match as it took place in the Quarter Finals of the Vanderbilt, the premier event at the Spring Nationals. 

Our team led by 34 IMPs after 32 boards of that 64-board match and our team was playing well. In the third quarter, however, it felt like Brad and I had been hit by a truck after playing against Meckstroth and Rodwell. They played about as well as I have ever seen anyone play and the hands came up well for their style. We were outscored 65-0(!) over 16 boards and got knocked out. The Nickell team eventually lost in the Final of the Vanderbilt to a team captained by our friend ^*BReese Milner^*N (and partner ^*BMarc Jacobus^*N, ^*BSam Lev^*N-^*BJohn Mohan^*N, and ^*BPiotr Gawrys^*N-^*BJacek Pszczola^*N). Congratulations Reese (and team) on a great win!

Well, beating these guys in a 7-board match to win the North American Swiss would not really compensate for our loss to them in the Vanderbilt, but this would be my only chance for revenge for a while. Brad and I sat down to face Paul Soloway and Eric Rodwell. Although these two are not regular partners, they have played together a lot over the years. Paul and Eric are both among the very best and most successful players in the world and I suspected (correctly as it turned out) that we would not gain much due to their lack of a regular partnership.

The match was going just fine until this week's deal came along. I hope you enjoy it!

Fred Gitelman
Bridge Base Inc.
^*Hwww.bridgebase.com^*N



